docs.abstract: As governments pull back on spending, companies are paying for private terminals, joining in renovations and even reopening an airport to commercial flights.
docs.snippet: As governments pull back on spending, companies are paying for private terminals, joining in renovations and even reopening an airport to commercial flights.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Paine Field, about 25 miles north of Seattle in Everett, Wash., was born in the 1930s as a New Deal project, it was envisioned as a major commercial airport for the region. But that never happened. Instead, it became known as the place where Boeing offers “North America’s only publicly available commercial jet assembly plant tour.”

headline.main: Private Money Takes On Bigger Role in Airport Projects
headline.print_headline: The Airport That Wasn’t Is Turned Into One

docs.abstract: The spacious terminal built for when the Tennessee city was a bustling air travel hub has become a half-deserted white elephant that the airport is spending millions to shrink.
docs.snippet: The spacious terminal built for when the Tennessee city was a bustling air travel hub has become a half-deserted white elephant that the airport is spending millions to shrink.
docs.lead_paragraph: MEMPHIS — The view from the chief executive’s office window at Memphis International Airport is as sweeping as it is dispiriting: On a recent afternoon, he could see 10 empty jet bridges and not a single airliner. Later, at the curb in front of the terminal, there were only three cars dropping off passengers, and inside, a pair of moving walkways carried just three people between them.

headline.main: The Trouble With the Memphis Airport: No Crowds
headline.print_headline: An Airport With Plenty of Air to Spare

docs.abstract: The doctor, Fatima Cody Stanford, was on a flight to Boston on Tuesday when she helped a fellow passenger who was distressed. Two flight attendants questioned whether she was a doctor.
docs.snippet: The doctor, Fatima Cody Stanford, was on a flight to Boston on Tuesday when she helped a fellow passenger who was distressed. Two flight attendants questioned whether she was a doctor.
docs.lead_paragraph: Dr. Fatima Cody Stanford was on a Delta flight from Indianapolis to Boston on Tuesday when she noticed the woman next to her showing signs of distress. So Dr. Stanford did what she was trained to do in more than a decade of experience as a doctor — she began to assist her.

headline.main: ‘Are You Actually an M.D.?’: A Black Doctor Is Questioned as She Intervenes on a Delta Flight

docs.abstract: Premium economy — offering more space than coach but at a lower fare than business class — is turning out to be popular among fliers and a huge moneymaker for the airlines.
docs.snippet: Premium economy — offering more space than coach but at a lower fare than business class — is turning out to be popular among fliers and a huge moneymaker for the airlines.
docs.lead_paragraph: Premium economy was first introduced by Eva Air and Virgin Atlantic in 1992 as a new travel option for long-haul passengers who wanted a bit of extra comfort. The cabin was successful for both airlines and in the years since, more companies like Singapore Airlines and Air New Zealand have introduced their own versions.

headline.main: How Much Are You Willing to Pay for a Few Extra Inches of Legroom?

docs.abstract: The airline said many oversized items, which it was charging $150 to check, will now be considered standard baggage and cost only $30.
docs.snippet: The airline said many oversized items, which it was charging $150 to check, will now be considered standard baggage and cost only $30.
docs.lead_paragraph: Effective immediately, American Airlines will no longer charge passengers $150 to check sports equipment like bicycles or surfboards, or musical instruments like a cello. Such items, which were previously considered oversize baggage, will now be covered by the regular $30 fee for checked luggage, as long as the item weighs less than 50 pounds. And come winter, or if you’re heading to the Southern Hemisphere, skiers will be able to include their skis and an equipment bag as a single item if the weight is below that limit.

headline.main: Taking a Cello or a Surfboard on a Plane? American Airlines Just Cut Its Fees

docs.abstract: Apps help guide the blind through airports. Smartphones help the deaf communicate. But tech’s advantages often stop at the door of the plane, train or bus.
docs.snippet: Apps help guide the blind through airports. Smartphones help the deaf communicate. But tech’s advantages often stop at the door of the plane, train or bus.
docs.lead_paragraph: Technology is fast changing how people with disabilities get to and then navigate airports and train and bus stations. But technology can go only so far: Its advantages usually stop at the door of the plane, train or bus.

headline.main: For Disabled Travelers, Technology Helps Smooth the Way. But Not All of It.
headline.print_headline: Tech Makes Life Easier for Disabled Travelers, Until They Board
